# Naming Conventions

**Objective**: Standardize naming conventions to ensure consistency and readability throughout the codebase.

**Context**: To apply for unifying code style and conventions.

## Explanation

Respecting strict naming conventions facilitates reading, understanding, and code maintenance. Each type of element follows a specific convention.

**Global rules:**

| Element                  | Convention         | Examples                                    |
| ------------------------ | ------------------ | ------------------------------------------- |
| Variables / functions    | `camelCase`        | `userName`, `fetchData`, `isLoading`        |
| React components         | `PascalCase`       | `CalendarGrid`, `UserProfile`, `Button`     |
| Files                    | `kebab-case`       | `calendar-grid.tsx`, `user-profile.ts`      |
| Feature folders          | Singular           | `calendar/`, `payment/` (not `calendars/`)  |
| Hooks                    | Prefix `use`       | `useCalendar`, `useAuth`, `useLocalStorage` |
| Constants                | `UPPER_SNAKE_CASE` | `MAX_FILE_SIZE`, `API_BASE_URL`             |
| Types / Interfaces       | `PascalCase`       | `User`, `ApiResponse`, `CalendarEvent`      |
| Enums                    | `PascalCase`       | `UserRole`, `PaymentStatus`                 |
| Test files               | `.test.tsx`        | `calendar-grid.test.tsx`                    |
| Private variables        | Prefix `_`         | `_internalState` (optional)                 |

## Practical Implementation Example

**Variables and functions:**

```ts
// ✅ Good: camelCase
const userName = "John Doe";
const isAuthenticated = true;
const totalAmount = 100;

function calculateTotal(items: Item[]): number {
  return items.reduce((sum, item) => sum + item.price, 0);
}

// ❌ Bad: other conventions
const UserName = "John Doe"; // PascalCase
const is_authenticated = true; // snake_case
const TotalAmount = 100; // PascalCase
```

**React components:**

```tsx
// ✅ Good: PascalCase
export function UserProfile() {
  return <div>Profile</div>;
}

export function CalendarGrid() {
  return <div>Calendar</div>;
}

// ❌ Bad: other conventions
export function userProfile() {} // camelCase
export function user_profile() {} // snake_case
```

**Files:**

```
✅ Good: kebab-case
- calendar-grid.tsx
- user-profile.ts
- payment-form.tsx
- use-calendar.ts

❌ Bad: other conventions
- CalendarGrid.tsx (PascalCase)
- user_profile.ts (snake_case)
- paymentForm.tsx (camelCase)
```

**Hooks:**

```ts
// ✅ Good: prefix "use" + camelCase
export function useCalendar() {
  const [date, setDate] = useState(new Date());
  return { date, setDate };
}

export function useAuth() {
  const [user, setUser] = useState(null);
  return { user, setUser };
}

// ❌ Bad: without prefix "use"
export function calendar() {} // Not a hook
export function getAuth() {} // Not a hook
```

**Constants:**

```ts
// ✅ Good: UPPER_SNAKE_CASE
export const MAX_FILE_SIZE = 5 * 1024 * 1024;
export const API_BASE_URL = "https://api.lyksia.com";
export const DEFAULT_PAGE_SIZE = 20;

// ❌ Bad: other conventions
export const maxFileSize = 5 * 1024 * 1024; // camelCase
export const apiBaseUrl = "https://api.lyksia.com"; // camelCase
```

**Types and Interfaces:**

```ts
// ✅ Good: PascalCase
interface User {
  id: string;
  name: string;
}

type ApiResponse<T> = {
  data: T;
  success: boolean;
};

enum UserRole {
  Admin = "ADMIN",
  User = "USER",
}

// ❌ Bad: other conventions
interface user {} // camelCase
type apiResponse = {}; // camelCase
```

**Feature folders:**

```
✅ Good: singular
- features/calendar/
- features/payment/
- features/user/

❌ Bad: plural
- features/calendars/
- features/payments/
- features/users/
```

**Booleans:**

```ts
// ✅ Good: prefixes is/has/should/can
const isLoading = true;
const hasPermission = false;
const shouldRender = true;
const canEdit = false;

// ❌ Bad: without prefixes
const loading = true;
const permission = false;
```

**Event handlers:**

```tsx
// ✅ Good: prefix "handle"
function handleClick() {
  console.log("Clicked");
}

function handleSubmit(data: FormData) {
  console.log("Submitted", data);
}

// Usage
<button onClick={handleClick}>Click</button>
<form onSubmit={handleSubmit}>...</form>
```

**Callback functions:**

```ts
// ✅ Good: prefix "on" for callback props
interface ButtonProps {
  onClick?: () => void;
  onSubmit?: (data: FormData) => void;
  onSuccess?: () => void;
}

// Usage
<Button onClick={handleClick} onSuccess={handleSuccess} />
```

## Variants or Exceptions

- Shadcn UI components follow their own convention (e.g. `button.tsx` in lowercase).
- Next.js files (App Router) follow Next.js conventions (`page.tsx`, `layout.tsx`, `route.ts`).
- Destructuring variables can be renamed: `const { id: userId } = user;`.

